history.content: It is allowed. It depends on what you want to get out of the class. EE122 is more mathy - as in calculating markov chain for queueing delay, calculating ethernet load, etc (more low level fundamentals). There will most likely be no "formal" project, you can design your own network project with no specs. I personally like 168 better because of the projects and structure of the class.

Hi there- CS 168 and EE 122 are considered different courses, so technically yes, you can do this. However, if you are EECS, and CS 168 is counting toward one of your requirements (ie upper division units) you will not be able to P/NP it.  You can't P/NP a technical course until all of your requirements are fulfilled. This can only be done if you're taking a technical course that doesn't count toward anything you need.

children.subject: To follow up, I've taken 4 upper division EECS courses as of Spring 2016. After this semester, I will have completed 7. Does this mean the P/NP policy only affects me from the next semester onwards, or will it apply for this semester? Even if I P/NP 168, I still have 2 other courses this semester that will count towards the requirement.

history.content:
I'm in CS 168 now, and I'm feeling that I'm not getting much out of the class. EE 122 goes much more in depth with the material, and I personally think that it might be more worthwhile to take that class instead. Can I P/NP CS 168 this semester (or even just complete it for a letter grade) and then do EE 122 next semester for a letter grade, or is this not allowed?

Thanks in advance.
